a month ago because a project that I was working inside. And then so the slogan, this

00:02:46.619 --> 00:02:52.979
is the slogan for GitHub Actions, automate your workflow from idea to a production. And

00:02:52.979 --> 00:03:02.460
that's pretty much what GitHub does, automates your project. And I was, I've been working

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:11.539
with a G-League coach and I'm working on creating a Shiny app for that coach. So it

00:03:11.539 --> 00:03:19.539
became used to help with the scouring. And when I was working on the project, I did to

00:03:19.539 --> 00:03:32.100
find a way to able to scrape the data from the G-League website in an automatic way.

00:03:32.139 --> 00:03:38.220
So I don't have to go every day and kind of do the scraping because, you know, G-League

00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:44.860
plays almost every day. And then coaches, once the game is over, they quickly go into

00:03:44.860 --> 00:03:50.419
the next one. So I want to make sure the data is updated as soon as possible. So I found

00:03:50.419 --> 00:03:59.899
the GitHub Actions was a good way to do it. So I'm kind of just give you a brief introduction

00:03:59.979 --> 00:04:09.500
of what GitHub Actions is and how to start it. So it's a tool from GitHub, of course,

00:04:09.860 --> 00:04:14.660
that can be used in a lot of different things. You can use it as a test. For example, if

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:20.579
you have a package, if you build a package and you did some small changes and you want

00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:30.380
to test it out, if you didn't break anything, you can use GitHub Actions to make sure the

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:39.619
package looks good. You can deploy your projects with GitHub Actions. So it depends on what

00:04:39.619 --> 00:04:48.059
is your goal. You can do a lot of different things. Most of the people use GitHub Actions

00:04:48.059 --> 00:04:55.140
for continuous integration. That's what it's most used for. You can use in a lot of

00:04:55.140 --> 00:05:03.540
different things. You can use AR, Python, all different language. But today, of course,

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:12.500
I'm going to talk about AR. So before anything, that's where you start. So you have to

00:05:12.500 --> 00:05:23.980
create a GitHub folder workflow. So you've got to make sure that it's exactly this way.

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:30.980
So you've got to put .GitHub slash workflows. And then you have to create the GitHub

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:37.459
Action, you've got to create an email file. And this here, that's what it will look like.

00:05:37.459 --> 00:05:44.500
I'll explain a little bit more as we're going. But definitely, you've got to make sure that

00:05:44.500 --> 00:05:53.540
it is exactly, you spell it exactly like this. Otherwise, it won't work. So the GitHub, for

00:05:53.540 --> 00:06:02.859
the most part, is five steps. And depending on how complex it is, you can have more jobs.

00:06:02.859 --> 00:06:07.779
So we'll have a little more steps. But the first one is the events. And what is the event?

00:06:07.779 --> 00:06:14.140
The event is what triggers your workflow. And these two that I have here are the most

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:22.459
common ones, I would say. But you can customize as much as you want. GitHub does a great job

00:06:22.459 --> 00:06:30.660
with the documentation and gives you a lot of examples. So the first trigger that you

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:42.100
do is by push or the pull request. So once you push, it triggers the workflow and will run

00:06:43.779 --> 00:06:51.619
your workflow or your GitHub Actions. Another way to do it is creating a cron. And if you're

00:06:51.619 --> 00:07:00.339
not familiar with the cron, it's a way you can just timing your workflow. And this part is

00:07:00.339 --> 00:07:10.339
actually what made me to use GitHub Actions. So I want to run the script or scrape the data

00:07:11.940 --> 00:07:17.059
every day in the morning. So the coach wants to go there, wants to go to the Shiny app

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:24.579
as updated data. And with this cron schedule, if you're not familiar with the syntax,

00:07:25.459 --> 00:07:32.660
so the first one here is for the minutes. The second one here is going to tell you the hours,

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:41.619
the third day of the month. The next one is the month. And then the last one is the days of the

00:07:41.619 --> 00:07:48.660
week. If you put the stars, it means that you will run this case every day of the month. It

00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:56.100
will run every day, every month, and it will run every day of the week. 30 here, because in the

00:07:56.100 --> 00:08:03.059
minutes, that means it's going to run on the minute 30. And then here, the hours, that means

00:08:03.059 --> 00:08:14.579
it's going to run in this case at 5 a.m. and 5 p.m. So if you use this trigger, your workflow

00:08:14.579 --> 00:08:24.820
will run every single day at 5.30 a.m. and then 5.30 p.m. And this is what I was kind of looking

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:39.140
for, so I don't have to go and run the script every single day. So the jobs is what you're going

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:51.140
to create to kind of tell the GitHub what you want to do. So it can either be run a script or run a

00:08:51.140 --> 00:09:08.820
test or labeled. And then each job runs as a runner. And then each job also has steps and actions.

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:19.780
And you need to give an ID to the job, and I'll explain a little bit why. And then

00:09:21.219 --> 00:09:30.500
usually you can run multiple jobs, depending on what you want, and also within the limit

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:37.539
of GitHub actions. GitHub actions is free, but it has a certain limit, the jobs you can run.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:47.940
For the most part, jobs are independent, meaning they run in parallel. But you can have an option

00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:55.619
where they're dependent on each other. And if you look here in this example here, you'll run job

00:09:55.619 --> 00:10:05.619
number one, and then you have job number two. But for job number two to run, job number one has to

00:10:05.619 --> 00:10:12.979
run successful. So given a practical example, actually in my case, so I'm trying to scrape

00:10:13.619 --> 00:10:21.219
data from the GLeague website. So that's my job number one. And then job number two would be

00:10:21.219 --> 00:10:31.619
deploying the Shiny app, for example. So to deploy the Shiny app, I need to have the data scraped

00:10:31.619 --> 00:10:38.340
successfully first. And then job three here in this situation is kind of the same way. So job one

00:10:38.340 --> 00:10:47.539
and job two got to run successful, so with no errors for job number three to run. So what are

00:10:47.539 --> 00:10:57.299
the runners? So the runners are type of machines where your job is run on. So GitHub does a good

00:10:57.299 --> 00:11:04.500
job at hosting virtual environments, and it pretty much covers all the machines. So we have Macs,

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:10.500
Linux, and Windows. But you can also do your own or create your own runner.

00:11:14.419 --> 00:11:18.179
And then of course, I mean, it depends what you want. So for example, if you want to

00:11:18.739 --> 00:11:25.299
check your package, that's going to influence what kind of

00:11:27.140 --> 00:11:36.979
runners do you need. Steps are also within the jobs. So with the steps, you can run commands,

00:11:36.979 --> 00:11:47.059
run tasks, or run actions. Again, those are in the limit as long as you stay with the user limits.

